03300nam a22004935i 9780300160802DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221991ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001608027 a10.12987/97803001608022doi  a(DE-B1597)625714  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPQ2613.I2bZ6637 1991eb 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a848/.912092221 aPollard, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAndre Gide :bThe Homosexual Moralist /cPatrick Pollard. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1991  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAndre Gide, renowned French essayist, novelist, and playwright, was also a homosexual apologist whose sexuality was central to the whole of his literary and political discourse. This book by Patrick Pollard—the first serious study of homosexuality in Gide’s theater and fiction—analyzes his ideas and traces the philosophical, anthropological, scientific, and literary movements that influenced his thought. Pollard begins by discussing Corydon, a defense of pederasty that Gide felt was his most important book. He then provided a historical and analytical survey of books that contributed to Gide’s perception of homosexuality, including works on philosophy, social theory, natural history, and medicolegal questions. Pollard goes on to investigate works of fiction—ancient and modern, European and Oriental—in which Gide saw homosexual elements. He concludes by considering the homosexual themes in Gide’s own works, analyzing the ways that Gide constantly tried to resolve conflicts between nature and culture, hypocrisy and honesty, corruption and sound moral judgment, anomaly and conformity, and sexual freedom and religious constraint. The book provides a new perspective on Gide’s work, a reconstruction of the moral and intellectual climate in Europe at the beginning of the twentieth century, and a substantial contribution to the cultural history of homosexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDidactic literature, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 0aEthics in literature. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezFrance. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aPollard, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016080240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300160802/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles